<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="41" type="female macroptera">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Female macroptera.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">
Bicoloured with head, thorax and abdominal segments 
<normalizedToken originalValue="VIII–X">VIII-X</normalizedToken>
brown, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="I–VII">I-VII</normalizedToken>
yellow but 
<normalizedToken originalValue="III–VII">III-VII</normalizedToken>
with brown median area; antennal segment I brown, II yellow with brown basal part, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="III–VII">III-VII</normalizedToken>
uniform yellow with 
<normalizedToken originalValue="VI–VII">VI-VII</normalizedToken>
a little darker apex, VIII brown. All legs yellow with fore and middle coxae and fore femora brown (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 17–22" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 17 - 22. Podothrips adult colour patterns 17 P. lucasseni 18 P. odonaspicola 19 P. semiflavus 20 P. femoralis sp. nov. 21 P. sasacola. Some important features of femoralis sp. nov. 22 mesopresternum and metathoracic sternopleural sutures. Scale bars: 200 microns." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures17-22" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/349333" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures17-22">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">
Head 1.2 times as long as wide, cheeks distinctly constricted towards base (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–6" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 6. Podothrips species head, pronotum &amp; fore legs 1 P. femoralis sp. nov. 2 P. lucasseni 3 P. luteus (from Okajima 1978) 4 P. odonaspicola 5 P. sasacola 6 P. semiflavus." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures1-6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/349331" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures1-6">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); ocellar setae minute; postocular setae pointed at tips, half the length of eye, wide apart from each other (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–6" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 6. Podothrips species head, pronotum &amp; fore legs 1 P. femoralis sp. nov. 2 P. lucasseni 3 P. luteus (from Okajima 1978) 4 P. odonaspicola 5 P. sasacola 6 P. semiflavus." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures1-6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/349331" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures1-6">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Mouth-cone short, maxillary stylets reaching base of postocular setae, maxillary bridge present. Antennal segment sense cones: III with 1+1, IV with 1+11, V with 2+2, VI with 11+2, VII with 1 dorsal (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 7–16" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 7 - 16. Podothrips species. 7 - 10 Antenna 7 P. femoralis sp. nov. 8 P. odonaspicola 9 P. sasacola 10 P. semiflavus. 11, 12 Base of forewing 11 P. sasacola 12 P. femoralis sp. nov. Some important features of P. femoralis sp. nov. 13 mesopresternum 14 Pelta 15 abdominal tergites IV-V 16 abdominal tergites IX-X." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures7-16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/349332" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures7-16">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">
Pronotum with no sculpture, am reduced, aa, ml, epim, and pa setae well developed with expanded apices, epim setae longest; notopleural sutures complete; basantra well developed, longer than wide (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–6" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 6. Podothrips species head, pronotum &amp; fore legs 1 P. femoralis sp. nov. 2 P. lucasseni 3 P. luteus (from Okajima 1978) 4 P. odonaspicola 5 P. sasacola 6 P. semiflavus." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures1-6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/349331" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures1-6">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Metanotum almost smooth; metathoracic sternopleural sutures well developed (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 17–22" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 17 - 22. Podothrips adult colour patterns 17 P. lucasseni 18 P. odonaspicola 19 P. semiflavus 20 P. femoralis sp. nov. 21 P. sasacola. Some important features of femoralis sp. nov. 22 mesopresternum and metathoracic sternopleural sutures. Scale bars: 200 microns." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures17-22" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/349333" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures17-22">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
). Fore femur expanded; fore tibia with a distinct apical tooth; fore tarsal tooth developed (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–6" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 6. Podothrips species head, pronotum &amp; fore legs 1 P. femoralis sp. nov. 2 P. lucasseni 3 P. luteus (from Okajima 1978) 4 P. odonaspicola 5 P. sasacola 6 P. semiflavus." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures1-6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/349331" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures1-6">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Fore wings slightly constricted medially, without duplicated cilia, sub-basal wing setae equal with length, S1 and S2 expanded at apex, S3 acute (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 7–16" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 7 - 16. Podothrips species. 7 - 10 Antenna 7 P. femoralis sp. nov. 8 P. odonaspicola 9 P. sasacola 10 P. semiflavus. 11, 12 Base of forewing 11 P. sasacola 12 P. femoralis sp. nov. Some important features of P. femoralis sp. nov. 13 mesopresternum 14 Pelta 15 abdominal tergites IV-V 16 abdominal tergites IX-X." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures7-16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/349332" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures7-16">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">
Pelta hat-shaped with pair of campaniform sensilla (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 7–16" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 7 - 16. Podothrips species. 7 - 10 Antenna 7 P. femoralis sp. nov. 8 P. odonaspicola 9 P. sasacola 10 P. semiflavus. 11, 12 Base of forewing 11 P. sasacola 12 P. femoralis sp. nov. Some important features of P. femoralis sp. nov. 13 mesopresternum 14 Pelta 15 abdominal tergites IV-V 16 abdominal tergites IX-X." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures7-16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/349332" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures7-16">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
); tergites 
<normalizedToken originalValue="II–VII">II-VII</normalizedToken>
with two pairs of wing-retaining setae (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 7–16" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 7 - 16. Podothrips species. 7 - 10 Antenna 7 P. femoralis sp. nov. 8 P. odonaspicola 9 P. sasacola 10 P. semiflavus. 11, 12 Base of forewing 11 P. sasacola 12 P. femoralis sp. nov. Some important features of P. femoralis sp. nov. 13 mesopresternum 14 Pelta 15 abdominal tergites IV-V 16 abdominal tergites IX-X." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures7-16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/349332" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures7-16">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
); abdominal tergite IX setae S1 and S2 pointed at apex, shorter than tube; tube 0.54 times as long as head; anal setae 1.7 times as long as tube (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 7–16" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 7 - 16. Podothrips species. 7 - 10 Antenna 7 P. femoralis sp. nov. 8 P. odonaspicola 9 P. sasacola 10 P. semiflavus. 11, 12 Base of forewing 11 P. sasacola 12 P. femoralis sp. nov. Some important features of P. femoralis sp. nov. 13 mesopresternum 14 Pelta 15 abdominal tergites IV-V 16 abdominal tergites IX-X." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures7-16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/349332" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures7-16">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="41" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Measurements</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">
(holotype female, in 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
). Total length 2440. Head length 260, width across behind eyes210; eye length 85, width 55; postocular setae length 40. Antenna length 440, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="I–VIII">I-VIII</normalizedToken>
length (width): 35(40), 50(30),55(25),60(30),55(25),50(25),52(25),35(22). Pronotum length 235, width 235; aa 12, ml 12, epim 45, pa 17. Fore wing length 960, sub-basal setae S1-S3 length 20, 15, 15. Pelta length 75, width 130.Tube length 140, anal setae length 240.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="41" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Specimens examined.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Holotype female. CHINA, Yunnan, Mengla County, on Bamboo leaves, 22.iv.1997, Y.F. Han. Paratype: one female with same data as holotype; one female, Fujian Prov., Xiamen City, on Bamboo leaves, 29.iv.1991, Y.F. Han; one female, Guangdong Prov., on Bamboo leaves, 29.iv.1992, Y.F. Han.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="41" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">
This new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. sasacola" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="sasacola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">P. sasacola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in forewing without duplicated cilia and body bicoloured, but differs in having all legs yellow with fore legs femora brown, antennal segment 
<normalizedToken originalValue="V–VI">V-VI</normalizedToken>
uniformly yellow and VII yellow with apical third brown (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 17–22" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 17 - 22. Podothrips adult colour patterns 17 P. lucasseni 18 P. odonaspicola 19 P. semiflavus 20 P. femoralis sp. nov. 21 P. sasacola. Some important features of femoralis sp. nov. 22 mesopresternum and metathoracic sternopleural sutures. Scale bars: 200 microns." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures17-22" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/349333" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures17-22">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
), meso- and metanotum brown, all developed pronotal setae expanded at apex (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–6" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 6. Podothrips species head, pronotum &amp; fore legs 1 P. femoralis sp. nov. 2 P. lucasseni 3 P. luteus (from Okajima 1978) 4 P. odonaspicola 5 P. sasacola 6 P. semiflavus." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures1-6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/349331" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures1-6">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), and fore wing sub-basal setae S1 and S2 expanded (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 7–16" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 7 - 16. Podothrips species. 7 - 10 Antenna 7 P. femoralis sp. nov. 8 P. odonaspicola 9 P. sasacola 10 P. semiflavus. 11, 12 Base of forewing 11 P. sasacola 12 P. femoralis sp. nov. Some important features of P. femoralis sp. nov. 13 mesopresternum 14 Pelta 15 abdominal tergites IV-V 16 abdominal tergites IX-X." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures7-16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/349332" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures7-16">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). In contrast, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. sasacola" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="sasacola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">P. sasacola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has all legs yellow, antennal segments 
<normalizedToken originalValue="V–VI">V-VI</normalizedToken>
yellow with apical half brown, VII uniformly brown, meso- and metanotum yellow (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 17–22" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 17 - 22. Podothrips adult colour patterns 17 P. lucasseni 18 P. odonaspicola 19 P. semiflavus 20 P. femoralis sp. nov. 21 P. sasacola. Some important features of femoralis sp. nov. 22 mesopresternum and metathoracic sternopleural sutures. Scale bars: 200 microns." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures17-22" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/349333" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures17-22">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
), pronotum aa, ml and pa pointed at apex, epim setae expanded (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–6" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 6. Podothrips species head, pronotum &amp; fore legs 1 P. femoralis sp. nov. 2 P. lucasseni 3 P. luteus (from Okajima 1978) 4 P. odonaspicola 5 P. sasacola 6 P. semiflavus." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures1-6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/349331" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures1-6">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
), and sub-basal setae S1 and S2 pointed (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 7–16" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 7 - 16. Podothrips species. 7 - 10 Antenna 7 P. femoralis sp. nov. 8 P. odonaspicola 9 P. sasacola 10 P. semiflavus. 11, 12 Base of forewing 11 P. sasacola 12 P. femoralis sp. nov. Some important features of P. femoralis sp. nov. 13 mesopresternum 14 Pelta 15 abdominal tergites IV-V 16 abdominal tergites IX-X." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures7-16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/349332" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures7-16">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
). It is also related to 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. odonaspicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="odonaspicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">P. odonaspicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. bicolor" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">P. bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Seshadri &amp; Ananthakrishnan in the bicoloured body, but this new species can be distinguished by forewing without duplicated cilia (forewing with duplicated cilia in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. odonaspicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="odonaspicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">P. odonaspicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and fore tibia with distinct subapical tooth (fore tibia without distinct subapical tooth in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. odonaspicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="odonaspicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">P. odonaspicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–6" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 6. Podothrips species head, pronotum &amp; fore legs 1 P. femoralis sp. nov. 2 P. lucasseni 3 P. luteus (from Okajima 1978) 4 P. odonaspicola 5 P. sasacola 6 P. semiflavus." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures1-6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/349331" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures1-6">Figs 1</figureCitation>
